-- South African Stocks Fall, Led Down by AngloGold Ashanti, Harmony, Merafe
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-12-17T13:24:10Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-17/south-african-stocks-fall-led-down-by-anglogold-ashanti-harmony-merafe.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  lost 88.17, or 0.3 percent, to 31,615.44 as of 2:49
p.m. in Johannesburg, trimming the gauge’s gain in the four
trading days of this week to 0.4 percent. The market was closed
yesterday for a public holiday.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG SJ), the world’s third-largest
gold producer, slumped the most since Sept. 15, losing 15 rand,
or 4.3 percent, to 331 rand. The FTSE/JSE Africa Gold Mining
Index fell as much as 4.4 percent to 2,708.41 and last traded
3.5 percent down, heading for its biggest slide since September .
Harmony Gold Mining Ltd.  (HAR SJ), Africa’s third-largest
producer of gold, declined 3.01 rand, or 3.4 percent, to 85.01
rand. Gold fell less than 1 percent, a third day of losses, to
$1,369.85 an ounce.  Capitec Bank Holdings Ltd.  (CPI SJ), the second-largest
South African provider of unsecured loans, rose 2.8 percent, to
a record 164.50 rand, and last traded 0.6 percent higher at 161
rand. The company said its 1 billion rand rights offer has
become unconditional and will proceed as planned.  Cenmag Holdings Ltd.  (CMG SJ), an investment group,
declined 20 cents, or 10 percent, to 1.80 rand, the lowest since
Nov. 25. The company said it received acceptances for 86,702
shares, or 1.45 percent of the stock it wanted to purchase in a
mandatory share buy-back.  Merafe Resources Ltd.  (MRF SJ), a ferrochrome producer,
retreated 2 cents, or 1.3 percent, to 1.55 rand. Merafe said the
European benchmark ferrochrome price has been settled  at $1.25
a pound for the first quarter of 2011, a 4 percent drop from the
fourth quarter of 2010.  O-line Holdings Ltd.  (OLI SJ), a manufacturer of cable
ladders, advanced to the highest intraday level since December
2009, gaining 5 cents, or 5.6 percent, to 95 cents. The company
declared a 2 cents dividend for the year ended June.  Wesizwe Platinum Ltd.  (WEZ SJ), a South African explorer of
the metal, jumped 6 cents, or 3.1 percent to 2.03 rand. Jinchuan
Group Ltd. of China, China-Africa Development Fund and Micawber
809 Ltd., a black investors group, will buy Wesizwe shares for a
combined $227 million, or about 1.86 rand a share, Wesizwe said
today in a statement. The deal gives the Johannesburg-based
company $877 million to build a platinum mine in South Africa,
the world’s largest supplier of the metal.  To contact the reporter on this story:
